---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Well Control & Kicks — Recognition, Shut-In, Kill Procedures"
  description="Complete well control reference: kick recognition signs, shut-in procedures, the driller's method vs wait-and-weight, and kill sheet calculations."
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Drilling', href: '/drilling' }, { label: 'Well Control', href: '/drilling/well-control' }]}
>
  <Nav slot="nav" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-eyebrow">Drilling — Emergency Procedures</div>
    <h1>Well <span>Control</span></h1>
    <p class="page-hero-sub">A kick is an influx of formation fluid into the wellbore because formation pressure has exceeded hydrostatic pressure. Every crew member must know the warning signs — early detection means a manageable situation.</p>
  </div>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div>
        <h2 class="section-title" style="font-size:28px;">Kick <span>Recognition</span></h2>
        <div class="safety-matrix">
          <div class="safety-item green">
            <h4>✅ Normal — Keep Drilling</h4>
            <p>Steady pit volume. Returns match pump output. Normal gas levels. Stable ROP and torque.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="safety-item yellow">
            <h4>⚠ Warning Signs</h4>
            <p>Increasing pit volume (0.5–2 bbls). Drilling break. Increase in return flow while pumps are constant.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="safety-item orange">
            <h4>🔶 Shut In Now</h4>
            <p>Pit gain greater than 2 bbls. Well flowing with pumps off. Any positive SIDPP/SICP after shut-in.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="safety-item red">
            <h4>🚨 Emergency</h4>
            <p>Uncontrolled flow at surface. BOP failure. Evacuate and activate emergency response plan immediately.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="danger-box mt-24">
          <strong>Never drill through a suspected kick.</strong> The moment any warning sign appears, stop making hole and pick up off bottom immediately. Hesitation is the single biggest factor that turns a manageable kick into a blowout.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="section-title" style="font-size:28px;">Shut-In <span>Procedure</span></h2>
        <div class="accordion">
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 1 — Detect & Stop Drilling</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>Immediately pick up off bottom. Stop making hole the moment a kick is suspected. Raise the string to clear the kelly/top drive.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 2 — Shut In the Well</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>Close the annular BOP (soft shut-in) or pipe ram (hard shut-in) per company procedure. Close the choke. Notify toolpusher and company man immediately.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 3 — Read Pressures</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>Allow pressures to stabilize (15–30 min). Record SIDPP, SICP, and pit gain volume — your inputs for the kill sheet.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 4 — Calculate Kill Mud Weight</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>KMW = OMW + (SIDPP ÷ (0.052 × TVD)). Add safety margin per company policy. Calculate ICP and FCP for the kill sheet.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 5 — Kill the Well</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>Driller's Method or Wait-and-Weight — both are valid, follow your company's approved procedure. See comparison below.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-item">
            <button class="acc-header"><h4>Step 6 — Verify & Resume</h4><span class="acc-arrow">▼</span></button>
            <div class="acc-body"><p>Confirm zero pressure and no flow before resuming. Investigate root cause before drilling ahead.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">Kill Methods</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Driller's Method vs <span>Wait-and-Weight</span></h2>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Process</th><th>Advantage</th><th>Disadvantage</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Driller's Method</td>
            <td>Circulate the kick out first at original mud weight while holding casing pressure constant, then weight up and circulate to TD in a second circulation.</td>
            <td>Can begin immediately — no time spent mixing kill mud first</td>
            <td>Two full circulations required; more time on well overall</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Wait-and-Weight (Engineer's Method)</td>
            <td>Prepare kill-weight mud first, then circulate the well in a single stage using the weighted mud.</td>
            <td>Single circulation — often faster overall, less annular pressure exposure</td>
            <td>Requires time to mix sufficient kill mud volume before starting</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p style="color:var(--fog);font-size:13px;margin-top:20px;max-width:700px;">Both methods are industry-accepted and taught in IWCF/IADC well control certification. Which one is used depends on company policy, kick severity, and available kill mud on location. Use the <a href="/calculators/kill-sheet" style="color:var(--amber);">kill sheet calculator</a> to run the actual numbers for either method.</p>

    <div class="note-box mt-24">
      <strong>BOP Pressure Checks (Daily):</strong> Accumulator pressure: <span class="highlight">3,000 psi</span> · Manifold pressure: <span class="highlight">1,500 psi</span> · Annular operating: <span class="highlight">700–1,500 psi</span> · Air supply to pumps: <span class="highlight">125 psi</span>. Full detail on the <a href="/equipment/bop" style="color:var(--amber);">BOP equipment page</a>.
    </div>

    <p style="color:var(--fog);font-size:14px;margin-top:24px;max-width:700px;">Ready to go deeper? The <a href="/pillars/advanced-well-control-and-hydrostatics" style="color:var(--amber);">Advanced Well Control &amp; Hydrostatics guide</a> covers TVD vs MD, ECD, the volumetric method, managed pressure drilling, and regional considerations for supervisor and engineer-level certification.</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
function toggleAcc(btn: HTMLElement) {
  const body = btn.nextElementSibling as HTMLElement;
  const arrow = btn.querySelector('.acc-arrow') as HTMLElement;
  const isOpen = body.classList.contains('open');
  document.querySelectorAll('.acc-body').forEach(b => b.classList.remove('open'));
  document.querySelectorAll('.acc-arrow').forEach(a => (a as HTMLElement).style.transform = '');
  if (!isOpen) {
    body.classList.add('open');
    arrow.style.transform = 'rotate(180deg)';
  }
}
document.querySelectorAll('.acc-header').forEach(btn => {
  btn.addEventListener('click', () => toggleAcc(btn as HTMLElement));
});
</script>
